title: Mount Marsland
text: Mount Marsland () is a <a href="mountain">mountain</a> standing south of the eastern part of <a href="Beaver%20Glacier%20%28Enderby%20Land%29">Beaver Glacier</a> in <a href="Enderby%20Land">Enderby Land</a>, Antarctica. It was plotted from air photos taken by <a href="Australian%20National%20Antarctic%20Research%20Expeditions">Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions</a> in 1956 and was named by the <a href="Antarctic%20Names%20Committee%20of%20Australia">Antarctic Names Committee of Australia</a> in 1962 for <a href="F.L.%20Marsland">F.L. Marsland</a>, a member of the crew of the "<a href="RRS%20Discovery">Discovery</a>" during the <a href="British%20Australian%20New%20Zealand%20Antarctic%20Research%20Expedition">British Australian New Zealand Antarctic Research Expedition</a> of 1929–31.
